english:
  title: On Policy
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Let me pose a question. The Analects tells us: "When the people are numerous, make them prosperous; when they are prosperous, teach them." It also says: "If a worthy person instructs the people for seven years, they can be sent to war." And again: "If a worthy person governs a state for a hundred years, cruelty and killing can be eliminated." Furthermore: "Lead the people through laws and regulate them through punishments, and they will avoid wrongdoing but have no sense of shame. Lead them through virtue and regulate them through rites, and they will have both shame and rectitude." These are all the words of sages, which scholars ought to hold dear in their hearts.

    Our realm serves the Yuan and enjoys peace both within and without. Villages flourish in neat rows, roads teem with travelers. The people multiply daily, the fields are opened daily—barren lands have become paddies, forests have become fields. Is this not abundance? Yet scarcely one or two in a hundred who receive name-fields actually pay their duties. The powerful families display vessels of gold and jade; merchants' wives trail silken robes. Is this not wealth? Yet eight or nine in ten exhaust their provisions repaying debts. We are fortunate to live in this enlightened age, where all under heaven share one culture. Every household keeps the writings of the Cheng-Zhu school, every person studies the learning of principle. The way of instruction seems within reach. And yet, how many among the scholars truly embody broad learning and steadfast conduct? How many among officials achieve virtue and realize talent? If even the learned fall short, what can we expect of the common people?

    Though worthy rulers have eliminated powerful ministers and established the new capital, and though loyal and steadfast sovereigns have succeeded one another, there were always capable ministers and able advisors worthy of the name "worthy persons." They guided and served, and prosperity has continued to this day. For long they have taught the people and governed the realm. But now Japanese raiders swarm like bees, launching boats to breach our borders. To drive them back and capture them, we must drain the resources of the poor to provision our armies and conscript farmers to fill our ranks. Yet we see no compliance when commands are issued, no cessation when prohibitions are declared—only hear of discontent and false rumors spread. How can this be called readiness for war?

    Those who fear losing their posts and the discontented stir troubles within the realm and hasten their own destruction. How can this be called the elimination of cruelty and killing? Though councils gather to deliberate, though officials sift through merit and demerit, though inspectors correct faults and the bench determines sentences, our ruler—gracious, compassionate, frugal, avoiding pleasure and indulgence, consulting the wise, honoring his ministers, restoring ancient rituals, performing sacrifices at the ancestral temple—governs through law, punishment, virtue, and rite. Yet the court lacks the grace of humble yielding, the countryside lacks harmonious customs. Strife and banditry abound. How can we hope for both shame and rectitude?

    Why is this so? You scholars, blessed to serve in a court that welcomes frank speech, under a ruler who desires good governance, must bring forth your deepest thought. Trace the roots of these disorders and propose ways to restore and invigorate the people. What you present, the officials shall bring before the throne and implement throughout the realm. Surely this is no small matter.
  footnotes:
    - The Analects passages cited are from the Analects of Confucius, particularly Books II, XIII, and XVI, which form the philosophical foundation of this policy critique.
    - The "worthy persons" (善人) and "virtuous governance" reflect Confucian ideals of moral leadership that should inform statecraft.
    - The poem addresses the Goryeo court of Lee Je-hyeon's time, referring to historical Korean rulers (the Loyal and Fierce kings, and the Loyal and Solemn kings) and critiques the gap between Confucian ideals and practical governance challenges including Japanese piracy and internal corruption.
